<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-060-916  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 060 916.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer andamp; Software News  Feb 6 1989 v7 n6 p24(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>California doctor computerizes the back massage. (Dr. Joseph Berg)(VAR Files) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Reisman, Averil.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Chiropractor Joseph Berg has developed a computer-driven system tohelp position a biophysiometer seat used in correctivebody-alignment treatment.andP;  The system consists of a Commodore 64Cmicrocomputer, a television and an Okidata 120 printer, and it hasrecently been enhanced to print skeletal drawings of before-,during-, and after-treatment positions.andP;  The biophysiometer seattilts the pelvis to gradually correct the spinal axis andcompensate for whatever imbalance was causing structuralmaladjustment or pain; patients by passively using the seat for afew minutes each visit 'imprints' the new position their autonomicnervous systems.andP;  Dr Berg envisions additional medicalapplications for his machine and is seeking a manufacturer ormarketer with whom to pursue this goal.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Commodore 64C (Microcomputer).andO;Topic:     ChiropracticMicrocomputersApplicationsMedicine.andO;Person:    Berg, Joseph (innovations).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>